name: Springfield Elementary School
details:
Springfield Elementary School (SES) is recognized as a Title I Distinguished School. The caring, dedicated staff members focus on providing meaningful instruction for every child, every day. A well-developed curriculum and instruction plan is the foundation of the successful academic program. Staff members have high expectations for all students. The instructional plan is data driven and allows for differentiation for all students.

 

Springfield Elementary provides an accelerated Gifted & Talented (GT) program in 1st – 5th grade. Students are served by the GT certified classroom teacher as well as a resourced GT teacher.  SES also provides an Early Intervention Program (EIP) for Kindergarten – 5th grade students. In addition, three Reading Recovery teachers provide one-on-one reading instruction for qualifying first grade students. The Reading Recovery teachers also assist with small group instruction in first and second grade. In addition to early intervention resources, SES provides quality special education programs for students qualifying for additional services. SES also receives services from an intervention team that provides one-on-one tutoring for qualifying students. SES is dedicated to ensuring that all students make academic gains throughout the school year.

 

In addition to quality instruction, SES provides thirty-one advanced technology classrooms. The students also benefit from two computer labs and several student computers in each classroom. A science lab is available for all hands-on learning experiences. Active learning and advanced technology classrooms increase motivation and participation to ensure that all students are actively engaged in the learning process.

name: Angel's Childcare & Enrichment Center II
details:
Sandra McLain opened Angel’s Child Care in her home over eight years ago “on a wing and a prayer” and three children. Since that auspicious beginning in 1994, Sandra has upgraded her facility to meet building codes to allow here to increase her enrollment. At the beginning of 2002, Angel’s Child Care had a full enrollment of 18 students, before and after school programs for older children and a long waiting list for infants and toddlers. It was time to expand the business and locate another facility.

With the help of the local Small Business Development Center, Sandra prepared a business plan for the new facility to make sure that the expansion was truly the best option for her business. Once that was completed, Sandra located the property she wanted to purchase for this expansion. Sandra found real estate in the heart of the City of Savannah that is easily accessible to downtown Savannah as well as the medical arts center of the city — the two busiest locations as far as employment is concerned. Sandra decided that she could offer an unique service to the medical arts area — flexible hours for people in the medical profession. The new facility will handle the overflow from the existing center as well as provide a referral outlet for parents interested in Angel’s Child Care.

Sandra completed the expansion plan process and approached SunTrust Bank for financing on the request. SunTrust put Sandra in touch with SBAC to package the SBA 7(a) loan request. The SBA approved the loan and Sandra was on here way to expanding an already successful business.

Angel’s Child Care now offers two facilities — the original one in Sandra’s home and the new one on 39th Street. Both centers provide top notch child care in loving environments. And, you can find Sandra moving between to the two facilities checking on her “children” on a regular basis.

name: Appletree Academy #1
details:
Founded more than 20 years ago and dedicated to providing a loving, safe, and supportive environment for children and their parents, Appletree  Academy I is located in the heart of Columbia County at 501 The Pass in Martinez.

We offer a wide range of childcare services for children ages six weeks to twelve years of age including all day care for nursery, toddlers, and preschoolers as well as before and after school care for nearby Columbia County public and private schools.  In addition, we offer care during school holidays as well as a summer camp for school age children.  We also offer two Bright from the Start, lottery-funded Pre-K classrooms.   

Appletree’s curriculum is a combination of High Reach Learning, and Pinnacle, as well as High Scope which is used in our Pre-K classrooms.     
These are all designed to provide a fun and stimulating learning environment for your children. We are also very excited to be able to offer extra opportunities in activities such as computers and music. All classrooms are set up with age-appropriate materials, adequate space, and access to one of three spacious playgrounds with age-appropriate toys and equipment.

Our highly trained staff are required to stay up to date in CPR, first aid, fire safety, and also maintain an additional 10 hours of approved child care training each year. Our Pre-K teachers must have their bachelor’s degrees and each paraprofessional is certified through at least a Child Development Associate degree. They must also complete an additional 15 hours of Pre-K training each year.

name: Arbor Montessori Enrichment
details:
Arbor Montessori School was founded in 1970 by 10 newly trained Montessori teachers. The school was originally called Montessori Child Development Center and had various locations around the city. In 1976, an elementary program was added to the already thriving primary program. The school’s name was changed the name to Arbor Montessori School in 1987 when the LaVista building was built because of the beautiful wooded campus. At that time, there were four primary classes: two at LaVista and two at the Emory location.

By 1997 the school had grown to include two upper elementary classes and so the administration decided to move forward with a middle school model. The building was renovated and expanded, and, in 1998, the Adolescent Program was started.  2014 marks the inauguration of our first toddler class. Arbor Montessori is one of only three schools in the metro area to provide a Montessori education from toddler through adolescence.

Arbor serves 310 students.  The school offers one toddler class (ages 18 months to 3 years), four primary classes (ages 2.5 to 6), three lower elementary classes (ages 6 to 9), two upper elementary classes (ages 9 to 12), and one Adolescent Program (ages 12 to 14).

name: Bible Baptist Day Care
details:
The Day Care at Bible Baptist Church opened in August of 2005. We have a unique approach in our teaching and development programs that set us apart from other Centers. It is our belief that learning begins at birth, and therefore children need continual stimulation and should be challenged at all ages, beginning at infancy.

The addition of the Day Care to the other ministries of the Church has enabled the Church to minister to people of all ages. Our mission statement at the Day Care is, "To always bring honor to our Lord Jesus Christ by fulfilling His will of training up children in the way they are to go. To love each child as Christ loves us. To educate and nurture their growth as individuals. To firmly ground them in the truth of God's Word. To establish a partnership with each parent to raise God's children together. To set a standard in childcare for quality care for our children and to provide an environment for childcare teachers that challenges and encourages them spiritually." name: Brenau Child Development Center
details:
Brenau Child Development Center has the unique responsibility of serving young children, their parents, the University community, and the community at large. As a reflection of our commitment to and our value of children, our first responsibility is to meet the needs of the children enrolled at the Center by providing care that is professional and predictable, yet warm and loving. The developmental stages of children must be continually recognized and considered to plan and implement learning experiences in the areas of cognitive, emotional, physical, and social growth.

The overall goal of the curriculum is to provide child-centered experiences that will help each child reach his/her maximum potential. Families are functioning systems that make up the immediate environment where individuals grow and develop; as such, the Child Development Center is an extended area of each child’s family. Brenau University students enrolled in teacher preparation, nursing, and occupational therapy have a unique advantage in being able to utilize the Center as an effective laboratory for applying sand synthesizing theoretical knowledge. We believe that care for young children in an academic setting can and should exemplify a balanced program which has intrinsic benefits for the children, their parents, and Brenau University students. From this perspective, we believe the Child Development Center has an opportunity for adding to the body of knowledge about the growth and development of young children with a responsibility for bringing pertinent information to parents about child development.

name: Broxton Elementary
details:
Broxton-Mary Hayes Elementary is a public, rural elementary school serving students in Pre-K through Fifth grade. In 1990, Broxton-Mary Hayes Elementary was established and served students in Pre-Kindergarten through Fifth grade. Broxton-Mary Hayes Elementary has been a Title I Distinguished School for ten years and currently maintains this recognition.

     Broxton-Mary Hayes Elementary is currently consists of one principal, one academic coach, one media specialist, one counselor, twenty teachers, six paraprofessionals, one nurse, one day porter custodian, four nutrition services personnel, one secretary, one computer operator, and four bus drivers. Teacher attendance at Broxton-Mary Hayes Elementary is excellent with an average of 97.6%. The 334 students at Broxton-Mary Hayes Elementary are divided into 14 classrooms. The average daily attendance for students is 96.9%.

     Parental Involvement is essential for success to be attainable at our school; therefore, it remains a focus as we make strides to push for academic excellence. Parents are involved in school business and decision making through our School Governance Council, PTO, PASS Class, Parent-Teacher Conferences, Open House, and Specific Curriculum Activity Nights.   Several of these parent communication opportunities were suggested by parents by surveys that they provided input through.

   Broxton-Mary Hayes is a loving community school that has embraced the slogan "YOU MATTER"! It is our aim to make sure that every stakeholder understands just how important they are to us. We look forward to a great school term and anticipate great successes as we aim to exceed expectations!

Welcome to Byne Christian School, the "Home of the Saints."  As the Headmaster of BCS, I am pleased to introduce you to our school.  BCS has a great heritage that spans three decades.

Byne Christian School is accredited, affordable, and growing.  We provide a Christian education for students in K-4 through 12th grade in a college preparatory environment that is ethnically diverse.  Our smaller class sizes afford our students a better chance to excel in all they do.

Our vision statement is:"Byne Christian School will be the standard for Christian Education in southwest Georgia academically, socially, and spiritually”:  
    We will glorify Jesus Christ in all we do and say.
    We will require mutual respect.
    We will give parents and students our best.
    We will strive for excellence.

name: Calvary's Kinder Academy
details:
Calvary’s Kinder Academy will aim to prepare children to excel as young leaders of tomorrow by combining an interesting, activity oriented curriculum tailored specifically for children with enhanced, first class care services. We offer a Christian based program, age specific curriculum activities, transportation to and from school and to extracurricular activities, as well as, after school program. We serve ages 6 weeks thru 12 years of age.

Our Christian child care learning center has professional care givers to enhance your child’s early cognitive, social-emotional, communication, physical and self-help skills. We want each child to know that he/she is a worthy person, acceptable and lovable just as God made him/her.

The security and safety, as well as, the caring and loving of your children are of utmost importance to us here at Calvary’s Kinder Academy. We look forward to sharing theses experiences with you and your children over the years.

name: Champions for Children
details: We believe all children need to have opportunities to learn and develop to their full potential. We believe it is important to have a safe, developmentally appropriate environment that encourages socialization skills, independence, and a positive self-image where children can develop at their own pace. Champions for Children is committed to serving the families and community by providing support and encouragement in a safe, healthy, nurturing environment.

name: Chattooga Early Head Start
details:
The mission of Family Resource Agency of North Georgia is to provide a comprehensive program which benefits children and families in the North Georgia communities served by the Head Start/Early Head Start and Pre-K programs. These services include meeting the educational, social, nutritional, health, emotional and psychological needs of the children and families served by the program.
Children in Head Start, Early Head Start and Pre-K attend classes four or five days a week in an environment which is conducive to learning. We encourage curiosity, exploration, problem-solving and self-expression. We assist children in developing a positive self-image. This is accomplished through active involvement with other children and learning to play together in a non-competitive atmosphere that includes successful experiences for all children no matter what skill level they may have achieved.

name: Chestnut Hill Academy
details:
Since 1998, CHA has been dedicated to developing global leaders one child at a time. The founders of the school focused on the development of the whole child — their intellectual, emotional, social, physical, and character development. This remains the aim of CHA today. The school strives to develop intelligent, thoughtful, and caring leaders with educated hearts as well as educated minds. We never lose sight of why we are really here and that is to prepare children for further academic challenges and to guide them to be responsible, compassionate, and active leaders of the world.

The academic program at CHA is notably challenging, but sufficiently flexible to meet the individual needs of children with varying degrees of readiness and ability. Although significant attention is given to the academic subjects and the co-curricular programs of Spanish, Music, Art, Technology, Physical Education, and Library, we believe that the growth of the whole child, including his or her attitudes and values, is as important as any particular academic discipline, knowledge, or skill.

CHA strives to have a diversified student body. We are a community of learners who value and are strengthened by the wide variety of our members. We believe that diversity unites the academic environment and is of paramount importance in preparing our children for life in an increasingly diverse and complex society. We are a school where individual differences are respected, welcomed, and valued.

The only way to fully understand the magic of CHA is to see us in action. We invite you to schedule time to come and experience for yourself the school’s unique way of educating student leaders to be knowledgeable, confident, and resourceful learners.

name: Chestnut Mountain YMCA Kids' Time
details:
The Georgia Mountains YMCA Kids' Time Afterschool Program makes a real difference in the life of your child because the program focuses on the development of the whole child through character building activities. Your child learns social skills, works on homework, participates in physical activities, connects with positive adults, and strengthens lifelong habits.

We believe the values and skills learned early on are vital building blocks for life. Because of the Y, more young people in neighborhoods around the nation are taking a greater interest in learning and making smarter life choices. At the Y, children and teens learn values and positive behaviors, and can explore their unique talents and interests, helping them realize their potential. That makes for confident kids today and contributing and engaged adults tomorrow.  Studies show that children who participate in YMCA School-Age programs:
    Are more cooperative as adults
    Are more likely to resolve conflicts by talking instead of hitting or fighting
    Improve their academic performance
    Become caring, responsible adults

name: Child Development Center at Central
details:
Early childhood experiences greatly influence a child’s self-esteem, ability to trust, and attitude toward learning. The Child Development Center of Central (CDC) seeks to support each child’s positive growth and development by providing an environment that is healthy, safe, loving, and stimulates cognitive thinking.

The CDC recognizes children as active learners who need active experiences with the world of people and things, as well as opportunities to plan, set goals, and assume responsibility.

Our classroom schedules, learning centers, furnishings, and playground allow children to explore, discover, and learn through developmentally appropriate activities.

We strive for a high-quality experience for young children and follow the guidelines recommended by the National Association for the Education of Young Children (NAEYC.)

name: Child's World Comprehensive Learning Center #2
details:
The Mission
“Child's World Comperhensive Learning Center prides itself in providing each child with quality care in a nurturing and positive learning environment.”  We believe that each child is important, unique, and entitled to respect as an individual.

Our centers are licensed by "Bright From The Start" Department of Early Care and Learning, and Quality Rated facility that offers one of a kind childcare services and an outstanding Pre-K-4 program. We offer a warm, caring environment that makes each child and parent feel special. Our program focuses on children ages 6 weeks to 12 years old.  We offer Before and After School Care, Extended Care, and Summer Camp.

We believe that for a child to be successful in his or her development, it requires teamwork from both the parents and the school. We are a play-based program that focuses teaching and learning through literature, music and art. Each classroom is equipped with 2 qualified teachers each possess no less than a CDA (Child Development Associate).

We believe that children learn best through natural consequences, curiosity and experiences. We have designed activities to provide for a child’s mind, body and soul. Experimentation, creativity, and discovery are all encouraged in a safe and healthy environment.

name: Children's Center at All Saints'
details:
Bright Horizons is the world's leading provider of employer-sponsored child care, back-up care, education and work/life solutions with more than 700 child care and early education programs and schools for employers and working families across the US, UK, Ireland and Canada. Committed to creating great work environments for its 18,000 employees, the company has been named 12 times as one of FORTUNE magazine's "Best Companies to Work for in America."

Bright Horizons provides work/life solutions for more than 800 leading employers to help them address challenges across key life stages. Programs include child care, back-up care, college counseling, elder care, and work/life consulting.

The first few years of life are an extraordinary time that sets the stage for all the years that follow. Our program for learning creates educational environments that empower children to be confident, successful, lifelong learners and socially responsible citizens. Bright Horizons' innovative programs help children, families, and employers work together to be their very best.

It's simple. Our mission is to achieve children's smiles through God's love.

Our spacious classrooms are designed to fit the needs of the children's age and developmental levels. Our spacious playgrounds providing lots of room for fun and play.

A component of this facility is Parent Interaction, which encourages parents to drop in anytime and to take part in classroom activities and special events. The interior classrooms, hallways, exterior exits and playground, are all monitored via a live surveillance security system. details: The Color Wheel mission is to encourage the growth and development of creative free thinking individuals. To this end, we provide safe, quality art based programs aimed at nurturing the whole child. Through the arts, we promote self discovery and high self esteem while providing a solution for Pre-School and After-School care. Color Wheel’s philosophy is based on the belief that through the arts children can attain a sense of self empowerment that is integral to the learning process in all areas academic, social and beyond. The daily exploration of one’s own creative ideas in a variety of medium encourages not only the natural curiosity and desire to learn but also independent thought and action.  We believe that children thrive in situations rich with experience, choice and personal responsibility. We recognize the value of a consistent supportive community of peers, mentors and parents.

name: Cornerstone Academy
details: Cornerstone Leadership Academy is a private non-profit school serving Dekalb and Rockdale counties of Georgia. We are an accredited school accredited by the Georgia Accrediting Commission. Guided by the motto, "Education is Freedom," we believe in educating a child to think creatively about the world we live in. Our curriculum allows our students to 'take chances, get messy, and make mistakes'. At the same time, a rigorous formal education is established that allows our students to excel in all areas of academics. In a typical day, our students may have meditated, recycled, analyzed an author's work, solved some advanced arithmetic problems, written a senator, and taken a nature walk.

name: Cornerstone Academy 2
details:
Cornerstone Academy's goal is to provide quality childcare in a Christ centered environment.  We combine accredited Bible based curriculum with knowledgable and professionally trained staff. Together we are molding God's most precious creation into our most valuable resource.

We partner with parents to help children build the right foundation for future learning and life.  We believe learning can be fun, and work hard to ensure your child is receiving the highest level of education in a fun and engaging environment. If you are looking for a child care center that is focussed on your child and their development, Cornerstone Academy is the right choice.  Stop by either of our daycare centers for a tour and see why Cornerstone is different from all the rest!

name: Cornerstone Early Learning Center
details: Cornerstone Early Learning Center was established in 1989 and is family owned and operated. Lana Elliott runs the day-to-day operations as Director. Assistant director, Dana Williamson, is just like part of the family and has been with Cornerstone since 1991.  We are open from 6:00am to 6:30pm Monday through Friday and provide care for children 4 weeks to 12 years of age. The early childhood classes are divided by age and development. Our program is a healthy blend of academics, life skills, and learning how to interact with other children. Nutritious meals include a morning snack, lunch and afternoon snack. Our before and after school program provides transportation to and from many area elementary schools, an afternoon snack, and homework help.

Our Child Care Quality Checklist will help you identify the factors necessary for you  in making the best decision for your child’s preschool education.

name: Creative Montessori School
details:
The Montessori method is a system of education that is both a philosophy of child development and a rationale for guiding such growth. It is based on children’s developmental needs for freedom within limits, as well as, a carefully prepared environment, which guarantees exposure to materials and experiences. It is designed to take full advantage of children’s desire to learn and their unique abilities to develop their own capabilities.

The basic tenet of Montessori education is that a child learns best in an enriched, supportive environment through exploration, discovery and creativity with the guidance and encouragement of a trained and caring staff.

name: Dutchtown Childrens Center
details:

We offer infant care for children one month old and up as well as a lottery-funded Pre-K program.  We welcome infants, toddlers, preschoolers, and school-aged kids, from six weeks of age to 12 years old.

At Dutchtown Children’s Center, we strive to help children develop good learning habits during their early years.  We create a top-notch program by providing an array of programs and services that both empower and nurture children during their most formative years.

As a family-owned and -operated business, Dutchtown Children’s Center is a community of compassionate professionals. We hire only the very best, and every member of our staff is a certified teacher.

     * Early Childhood Education

name: Eagles Landing Daycare and Learning Center
Eagles Nest Children's Center
details:
The purpose of the Eagle’s Nest Children’s Center is to provide a nurturing environment where children ages 6 weeks through 4 years can receive developmentally appropriate care during the hours of 7:00 A.M. to 6:00 P.M. The Eagle’s Nest Children’s Center operates Monday – Friday, year round. Summer care is available for children ages 5 to 12 for a limited number of weeks each summer. This center is a non-profit ministry of The Methodist Home for Children and Youth, providing child care services to staff of the Methodist Home, as well as families in the community.

Eagle’s Nest Children’s Center supports and encourages each child’s individual development – social, emotional, cognitive, physical, and spiritual. We believe that children learn through discovery in their play experiences. Learning centers and a robust curriculum provide enrichment and support the needs of each individual child.

Each child becomes a part of the Methodist Home’s extended family. Parents are encouraged to be involved in all of the ministries provided by The Methodist Home and share with us in providing the highest level of care for all the children and youth served at The Methodist Home.

The Eagle’s Nest Children’s Center is nationally accredited by Council on Accreditation’s Early Childhood Education, the United Methodist Association’s Health and Welfare Ministry’s EAGLE Accreditation and the National Early Childhood Program Accreditation (NECPA).

name: Eastside Elementary
details:
Eastside Elementary is the newest of seven schools that make up the Grady County School System. Eastside was formed by joining the "old" Beckbranch School, formerly located in Calvary, Georgia, closed during desegregation and consolidation and was reopened in 1973 for the county's kindergarten unit for the next 10 years. During the 1984 school term the school was literally moved 16 miles to Cairo and became the rear half of the new Eastside Elementary School. Nine rooms and a media center were added during the two-year construction transition.

Students and teachers were drafted as a result of redistricting Northside and Southside schools. During this time, all in-town elementary schools became kindergarten through fourth grades. In 1993, 5th grade was moved from the middle schools to each elementary school.

In 1992, nine classrooms were built, in 2002, eight additional classrooms were built, a new physical education building was built and was ready for the opening of the 2005-2006 school year. In the fall of 2005 construction began on nine additional classrooms. 

Through the years, Eastside has grown both in student number and physical size; this year enrollment is up more than 60 students.  The Eastside School district is experiencing growth between Cairo and Thomasville, therefore, increasing the school enrollment. Our school is comprised of 333 female students and 334 male students, 667 total students.  We come from different ethnic backgrounds:  African-American - 251, Asian - 3, Hispanic - 83, Indian - 1, Multi-Racial - 23, and White - 306. (as of 10-1-07)  

Eastside serves as the home of the county's Special Education Pre-K program and the class for the severe/profound Intellectually Disabled students. 

Our faculty is dedicated and diverse.  We have 47 teachers, 24 paraprofessionals, 4 custodians, 7 lunchroom workers, 1 media specialist, 1 counselor, 1 instructional coordinator, 1 assistant principal, 1 principal assigned to Eastside.  We share Art, Music, and EIP teachers with Southside and Northside on a 12 week rotation. 

The theme at Eastside for 2010-2011 is "Building Our Futures."  We look forward to serving the students of Grady County.  Please call or come by if you have any questions.  We are "Building Our Futures" in 2010-2011.

name: ECDC Barrow County Early Head Start
details:
Head Start is a federal program that promotes the school readiness of children ages birth to 5 from low-income families by enhancing their cognitive, social and emotional development.

Head Start programs provide comprehensive services to enrolled children and their families, which include health, nutrition, social services and other services determined to be necessary by family needs assessments, in addition to education and cognitive development services. Head Start services are designed to be responsive to each child and family’s ethnic, cultural and linguistic heritage.

name: Economic Opp. for Sav.-Chat. Co. Area Inc.
details:
Head Start is the City of Savannah’s largest community based mainstream early childhood education program. The program is funded by the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services and is designed to service the educational, psychological, and health needs of low-income families. The EOA Head Start program serves 824 children three to five years of age and offers high quality early childhood education, mental health, disability, medical, nutritional, and social services support for families.

In 1998, our program was expanded to include Early Head Start. The EOA Early Head Start program serves 75 children birth to two years of age, and provides services to pregnant mothers. Research has shown that cognitive development begins as early as birth; therefore; it is imperative that we provide educational opportunities that encourage healthy brain development. Like Head Start, Early Head Start also promotes a holistic approach comprised of an array of services provided to children and families.

The Head Start program makes a concerted effort to recruit Hispanic children and families.

Head Start reached out to these communities by employing bilingual staff and translating our print media into Spanish. As a result, we have enrolled more Hispanic children and families now than ever in our forty plus year history.

EOA Head Start understands that exposing pre-school children to different cultures and languages helps stimulate their cognitive growth. This is why Head Start teaches basic Spanish to its students.

details:
Elcan-King (EKE) was constructed during the years of 1954 and 1955. The school's name is unique because it was named after a former school superintendent, E.G. Elcan, and a former local principal, Grace King. These names combined together to form our school name Elcan-King.
    The school was renovated in 1993, adding a gymnasium, a media center, and additional classrooms increasing the total square footage to 57,489. Elcan-King is the home of 480 cougars, in grades Pre-K through 4th.
    Committed to the development of each child through academic achievement and promotion of self-worth, we all strive to reach our motto, "Climbing to Greater Heights." We are proud of the Highly Qualified professional credentials of our teaching staff.
    Currently our certified staff hold degrees in the following areas: 12 individuals with a Bachelors degree, 10 certified at the Masters level, and 9 individuals with a Specialist degree. EKE has 18 paraprofessionals/teacher's aides who work under the direct supervision of our highly qualified teachers. These individuals provide support for our kindergarten, special education, and Title I students. In addition to the certified and classified teachers, we have two clerical positions, six nutritional staff members, three custodial staff members, and one resource officer who is shared by other schools in the county.

name: Flowery Branch Elementary
details:
The community of Flowery Branch is located approximately 50 miles north of Atlanta.  It is a beautiful small-town community near Lake Lanier and also the home to the Atlanta Falcons.  The close proximity of Flowery Branch to Lake Lanier, the mountains, and Atlanta offers a wide variety of recreational and cultural activities.  Flowery Branch Elementary is located in the southwest corner of the county.  Flowery Branch Elementary opened in 1973 at the current location.  The building has gone through several renovations and additions over the past 30 years.
We currently have 604 students attending grades K-5.  We also house two Ninth District Pre-K classes and a Hall County special-needs Pre-K.  Our staff consists of 63 members, of which 42 are certified teachers.   We have an average daily student attendance rate of 96.25% while our average daily teacher attendance rate is 97.3%.
Valuable programs that are available to our students are chorus, a piano lab, Advance, Read Across America, 4-H,  as well as Dreambox Theater, Science Olympiad, and a Veteran’s Day assembly;  all of which have been added in the past three years.  We also have special showcase nights spotlighting individual grades and their student achievement.  The importance of living a healthy and active lifestyle is another area of focus for Flowery Branch Elementary.  Within the past three years, we have participated in the Alliance for a Healthier Generation, Health M Powers and Power Up for 30.
Flowery Branch Elementary embraces community involvement to care for the Whole Child. Our current Partners in Education include Chick-fil-a, Publix, and Flowery Branch Chiropractic. Our students also receive support from PTO, parents, and numerous volunteers.

name: Friendship House
details: In 1957, a small group of church women began a ministry in the Dalton neighborhood that helped lower income families. By 1958 Friendship House was established to serve the needs of neighborhood children and their families. Friendship House established a kindergarten, a mother's club, scout troops, and a summer program. Urban renewal moved Friendship House to a new neighborhood and became a full-time child care program. Today, Friendship House is located at 1300 S. Hamilton Street in a state-of-the-art facility. Friendship House offers preschool education and child care for 100 children between 6 week old to 5 year olds. Friendship House offers these services from 6:30 AM- 5:30 PM.

The Friendship Difference is immediately noticeable upon entering our school. Children enter the school through our two story forest where tall trees and friendly animals greet and inspire their young minds. We utilize a whole child approach to teaching, from our fun lobby to our engaging classroom organization; every child is engrossed in intellectual, physical, emotional and social levels of learning and development.

Our HighScope curriculum balances fun and education with stimulating hands on inside and outside activities to encourage your child’s interest and excitement for learning. Our experienced and educated staff fosters your child’s natural curiosity for learning throughout the day during collaborative circle time, dynamic classroom centers and cooperative recreational play.

business hours: 6:30 am until midnight, Monday through Friday

name: Grace Christian School Extended Care
details:
Grace Christian School started in the fall of 1979 under the leadership of Walter Lee Hodges, former pastor of Grace Baptist Church of Columbus, Georgia. We are happy to say that our doors have been open these many years to the greater Columbus area inluding Harris County, Muscogee County, and Ft. Benning, GA, as well as Phenix City, Smiths Station, and Ft. Mitchell, AL. GCS holds to the philosophy that education from a Christian perspective is the only true form of education.  Two outstanding elements contribute to the school’s philosophy of education:  first, our curriculum is Bible-based and Christ-centered.  Second, our staff consists of dedicated Christian teachers who are concerned about their student’s physical, mental, and eternal welfare.

     

The school’s primary objective is to show children how to live rather than just how to make a living.  The truths of the Bible are not substituted or separated from academics at GCS.  Instead, they are integrated into the entire educational program.  Standards of discipline and conduct are Bible-based to develop Christian character and sound values. GCS strives to maintain a truly Christian philosophy of education, high academic standards, and the proper emphasis upon morals, discipline, and social development.

Our program is designed to induce learning through repetition, hands on experience and active play which will foster independence while teaching respect for self and others. Our mission is to provide a safe learning atmosphere for your child’s development.

name: Green Tree Learning Center
details:
GreenTree Learning Center serves residents of Village Green Apartments, teen mothers attending high school, families enrolled in TCC-CIS’s Early Childhood Education Initiative, and others when space permits.
GreenTree Learning Center is licensed by Bright from the Start, Georgia Department of Early Care and Learning, which promotes a healthy, safe and high quality child care environment.
GreenTree Learning Center is approved for 36 children between the ages of 6 weeks and 4 years old. Additional programs will be added when funds become available.
GreenTree Learning Center employs at least three childcare teachers. The teachers use the Active Learning Curriculum and plan activities for the children which are developmentally appropriate, using materials to promote large and small muscle development, language skills and physical development.
Additionally GreenTree Learning Center provides workshops for parents addressing their needs and needs of children, and two Family Support Workers assist families participating in the Early Childhood Education Initiative.

name: H. T. Edwards Teaching and Learning Center
details:
The Early Learning Center (ELC) is proud to be part of the Clarke County School District’s vision as an innovative teaching and learning center housed on the H.T. Edwards Campus. The campus located on Dearing Extension includes the Athens Community Career Academy (440-1 Dearing Ext.), the Early Learning Center (440-2 Dearing Ext.), the Classic City High School (440-3 Dearing Ext.) and the Boys and Girls Club (440-4 Dearing Ext.).

The Office of Early Learning (OEL), housed in the ELC, oversees operation of the school district’s early childhood education programs. These include the state lottery funded Pre-Kindergarten Program, federal Early Head Start and Head Start, Preschool Special Education, Striving Readers and Early Reading First. Through collaboration among these programs, the Clarke County School District’s Office of Early Learning serves over 1200 students. Approximately 150 of these children are served at the Early Learning Center (ELC).

Other services provided at the ELC through collaborative community partnerships include the University of Georgia Professor in Residence and the Department of Family and Children Services/Job Placement Services.

The lion is our ELC school mascot and blue and gold are school colors. Our center was specifically designed to be appropriately sized for our children, from the cafeteria tables and chairs to the toilets. Outdoor play areas are designed and equipped with play equipment that targets young children’s fine and gross motor development. An indoor activity room is also available for the same purpose during inclement weather.

The ELC has a media center and a staff member who maintains books, games, videos and other age-appropriate resources that parents and teachers can check out. Classrooms also visit the media center for weekly story time.

name: Hallmark Heights Head Start
details: Head Start is a comprehensive early childhood development program for economically disadvantaged preschool children and their families. The objectives of this program are: (1) to improve the child’s health; (2) aid the child’s intellectual, social, and emotional development; (3) improve and expand the child’s ability for self-expression; and (4) help both the enrollees and their families gain greater confidence, self-respect, and dignity. Eligibility guidelines require that enrollees, including children with disabilities, are between three years of age and compulsory school attendance, and at least ninety percent are from low-income families.

PRIMETIME is offered at 9 licensed school-based sites: Norman Park, Odom, Sunset, Doerun, Okapilco, R.B. Wright, Funston, Hamilton and Cox. An additional site is conducted at the Y for the overflow of Sunset students only. A typical PRIMETIME day includes structured play, either outside or in the gym, a healthy snack, themed activities and free playtime. Homework help is offered for those who want their children to participate. Certified teachers study with these children 2 days per week during PRIMETIME hours. - See more at: http://www.moultrieymca.org/main/primetime/#sthash.C2HXLPXq.dpuf

details: Our beautiful school was constructed in 1988. name: Kinder World Daycare And Learning Center
King David Academy
details:
The kindergarten preschool of King David Academy is an object of great pride and care for both the administrators and the everyday staff of the Center. At this point it is impossible to remember how much time, strength, planning, disputing, and sleepless nights we here at King David have invested in to creating a paradise for young children – providing healthy meals, comfortable accommodations, interesting activities, and specialized preparation for the rest of your child's academic career.

 The daycare currently functions in four different age groups, educating children ranging from as young as two-months-old, all the way up to five years of age. Diverse subjects are taught by literate, well-educated, and professional instructors, that employ a wide variety of teaching methods. Also, the universal law for our instructors is the equal, respectful treatment of every child in their care – “A child is a person just like us, only still little.”

 In accordance to the different age groups and personalities in our day-care, we have put in place several different programs to promote the healthy and well-educated development of each little individual in our care. For instance: the Young Mathematician program, Young Researcher, “The Shelf of Wise Books”, and the Drama Hour. Special attention is also paid to the development of language and speech – as most of our students come from Russian-speaking homes, for whom it is important to enter school with a certain level of English language skills, while maintaining their native, Russian language. And the professional instructors at King David Academy are well-practiced in overcoming such challenges.

 The aesthetic development of children is also skillfully fueled by programs like music lessons, dance and choreography classes, and regular literature and fiction readings.

 However, we at King David Academy are also well-aware that child-care is not only a labor of creating a well-rounded and well-adjusted personality, but also, above all, the responsibility to ensure full and proper physical development of each child entrusted to us. Therefore, along with the many educational programs and healthy nutrition, the Center also gives great importance to exercise – the importance of a child's daily life properly alternating periods of physical activity and rest, productive waking-hours and restful sleep. Thus, daily walks and outdoor activities remain mandatory – so that you may be sure your child will get at least an hour and a half in the fresh, open air; which in turn will positively affect their appetite, learning ability, and improve the quality of day-time sleep.

 Surely, nobody can deny the importance of self-sufficiency and independence in child development – every family remembers their child's first steps, first self-made breakfast, first properly-tied shoe-lace. And here at King David Academy we are the same kind of family, and value each milestone in the development of the children under our care just as much. We also teach your child things like making the bed, cleaning up their toys, and being polite and friendly; but we do so skillfully, and without the child noticing that they are being taught, in the form of games, and in making learning fun – because the little one cannot, and should not, feel any outside pressure on their own growing-up, as it may cause conscious or subconscious protest. And, once again, the specialists at the Community Center are well-versed in such nuances of child-care.

 The day-care at King David Academy successfully competes with, and greatly overcomes, other day-cares. The Center has been certified as a “Center of Distinction”, is NAEYC accredited, and is among the few organizations involved in model pre-school education in the United States.

name: Kingsley Elementary
details: It is my belief that as educators and parents we must strive for a clear and focused mission that is designed to prepare all students to be successful, productive adults. As adults they will need to be able to work cooperatively together in an ever-changing world utilizing organizational, problem solving, and communication skills. Successful adults just don’t happen. Continuous learning is the key. Learning is not an isolated event, but an interactive, on-going, daily process that involves everyone – parents, staff, and students. Our goal is to help students to be life-long learners and successful adults by modeling the process and providing enriching experiences as well as challenging academics in a safe, creative, and positive environment.

We have used a substantial part of our Title I Budget to secure additional teaching staff to support mathematics instruction. These staff members will work with the homeroom teachers to close gaps in student learning and present content in a new and engaging manner. In addition, we are providing students with daily character lessons to include respecting others, table etiquette and how to interact appropriately with their peers. We understand that parents are providing these lessons daily but also recognize how beneficial it would be to reinforce these concepts at school. As always we look forward to working with your child and have high expectations for the 2014-2015 school year.

The purpose of the Head Start program is to “promote the school readiness of children ages birth to 5 from low-income families by enhancing their cognitive, social and emotional development”. Head Start  is a federally funded child care program which “provides comprehensive services to enrolled children and their families, which include health, nutrition, social services and other services determined to be necessary by family needs assessments, in addition to education and cognitive development services” (ACF, 2013).

The LaGrange Head Start Center is accredited through the National Association for the Education of Young Children (NAEYC) which is the world’s largest organization working on behalf of the young child.

details: At Legacy Academy our mission is to serve our children, families, staff, and communities in a manner that positively impacts their lives. name: Legacy Academy for Children #1
details:
Our mission is to teach our children to love God and develop a passion for learning. As part of the Charlotte Mason style of education, we believe in viewing and educating the child as a “whole person,” capable of appreciating the beauty of God’s world.


Charlotte Mason’s motto was, “I am, I can, I ought, I will.” Her emphasis on character development is central to all learning. We must first seek to reach our children’s characters; feeding their minds can only be accomplished with hearts that are open and sensitive.


Our standards are rigorous, but our methods aren’t dry and dull. At all costs, we avoid pointless field trips, poorly written books, repetitive busywork or dull textbooks. Our God has filled this world with wonders, and we wish to introduce our children to them while their minds are malleable and young.

 

To that end, we enjoy enriching field trips involving plays, musical performances, and cultural enhancement. We read living books: literature that has stood the test of time for quality of subject matter and authorship. Our seatwork includes classical techniques such as narrations to build the habit of attention, copywork of famous literature to build grammatical awareness, and independent creative writing to help our children’s minds soar.

 

Central to all our studies is a deep respect and reverence for the Bible. Memorizing God’s word, learning Bible stories, singing beautiful worship songs, and understanding the history of the church are integral to a well-rounded education.

    

To develop our curriculum, we pull from the best of the educational world, choosing resources that reinforce our underlying philosophy. Our books and materials will vary from year to year based on the unit studies we are enjoying, but our standards remain the same: quality materials that reinforce grace, peace, and truth.

 

As LHA flows from year to year, we seek like-minded families to join us, families who are committed to following Christ in their homes and who seek a Christian education for their children, in accordance with LHA’s values and educational methods.

Our Weekly Charges Are Only $75.00 Dollars Or $20.00 Dollars A Day For Drop In's. The Children Come In And Eat Breakfast  At About Eight O'clock The Children Are Moved To The Rooms For Their Lesson And Playtime Inside. Then At Eleven The Younger Childern Eat Lunch And About Twelve The Younger Children Lay Down For A Nap Until Two O'clock. The Older Children Eat At Eleven Thirty And About Twelve Thirty They Lay Down For A Nap Until Two Thirty. The Children Get Up And Eat A Snack Then Depending On The Weather The Children Will Go Outside And If Not They Will Play In The Rooms. After Their Play Time Done It's About Time To End The Day At North Thompson And The Children And Teachers Come Inside And Wait Until Their Parents Arrive To Pick Them Up. Then The Next Day It Starts All Over Again The Same Unless We Have Planned Partys Or Events For The Day Which You'll Know About Before They Happen.

name: Northeast Georgia Medical Center Day Care

details:
Northside Hospital Child Development Center is dedicated to supporting employees and associates by providing a developmentally appropriate program for children. We recognize that a child’s early years provide the foundation for later development. A young child, therefore, needs time to participate in experiences that provide a secure foundation for the future.  Development is a truly fascinating and wonderful phenomenon and should not be accelerated or skipped. Each period of a child’s development should be allowed to evolve according to the individual child.

The program provides each child an individualized curriculum implemented by highly trained and experienced, caring adults. This curriculum is based on the philosophy that learning develops through play, which is the primary vehicle through which children learn.  Play is an avenue for self-expression and for organization of the world.  We believe that learning occurs when children are actively involved with people and materials in their environment.  Such learning is facilitated in a loving, home-like atmosphere that provides a variety of challenging but non-stressful activities and materials.

Our program provides an atmosphere that emphasizes understanding and acceptance of all children and families where differences are understood, respected, encouraged, and mediated when necessary.

details:
Situated conveniently just west of Georgia 400 in Alpharetta, Georgia, Oak Grove Academy is a private school designed to meet the needs of contemporary children as they embrace the world of learning. As a private, non-franchise early childhood learning center, the Oak Grove Academy owners, management, and staff have created a unique, caring, inviting, yet stimulating learning environment.

Oak Grove Academy was opened in 1999 by grandparents with a desire to create a special place for their grandchildren. Several years later, they find themselves the grandparents to 170 or more happy children. Their unique hands-on approach is evident by their presence and caring relationship with each family. Parents and children instantly feel the loving atmosphere and pleasant environment offered by these grandparents.

We are proud of our accreditation by the Georgia Accrediting Commission, Inc. We provide 20 hours of accredited training each year in addition to CPR, First Aid, and Fire Safety training for our staff to enrich your child's early childhood care and learning experiences. We believe that we must create a partnership with our parents in order to provide this environment of love, learning, laughter, and safety for EACH child. Our shared goal is to provide our children and families a positive and rewarding experience!

Many of the local private and public elementary schools recommend Oak Grove Academy to their potential parents. They cite the advanced curriculum, structured program, caring environment, knowledge and experience of the teaching staff. The general preparedness of the students entering their schools after attending Oak Grove Academy is noticeable to other educators.

name: Play to Learn Daycare and Learning Center

details:
The Rebecca Blalock Child Development center has a rich and long history of service to students community members int he Rome/Floyd County Area.  What began as a dream soon became a reality as the desire to provide a safe and nurturing environment for your African-American boys and girls to stay while their fathers and mothers worked.  That desire birthed the first nursery school in Rome for black children.  It was called the Rome Nursery for Negro Children.  It began in the basement of Ebenezer Presbyterian Church at West First street and Smith street.  She went door to door soliciting donations, equipment, and furnishings.  She was able to secure federal funding for her nursery school through a New Deal Program, the Works Progress Administration.

Following her death, African American citizens elected to change the name of the Rome Nursery for Negro Children to the Rebecca Blaylock Nursery.  The school has been in operation continuously since 1934.  There are two locations for the Rebecca Blaylock Child Development Center at 606 Graham Street and 500 Cedar Avenue where children of all races are served.

The development center's mission is "..to provide a secure and positive environment of daycare with emphasis on developmental skills in five areas of growth for children and stabilization of adult clients in financial planning, parenting skills, educational and emotional growth."

This remarkable place is run by a devoted caring staff and lead by Dr. Janice Merritt.  Dr. Merritt's love, devotion, and commitment to children are as evident as those of Ms. Rebecca Ellen Blaylock.  Her leadership and guidance perpetuate the legacy of quality education to all children.

RPS was opened in August 1999 with e-Splost Funding as a solution for the overcrowding at Ringgold Elementary School. The 87,000 square foot facility adjoins RES but is a separate facility. The two schools share a kitchen and a large Media Center.

In the Ringgold Primary School community, stakeholders work together to create a positive and secure learning environment with high expectations for student growth. name: Saint Francis Xavier Preschool
details:
Our Mission
St. Francis Xavier Catholic School is a Christ-centered school built on a strong foundation of Gospel values, empowering all to lead faith-filled lives.

Our History
Founded by the Sisters of St. Joseph, St. Francis Xavier School began as St. Joseph's School and was established in Brunswick in 1900. Reverend P. J. Luckie, S.M., requested Rt. Reverend Benjamin J. Keiley, D.D., Bishop of Savannah,  open a Catholic school in St. Francis Xavier parish. The Sisters of St. Joseph started and staffed the school in September of that same year.

A former boarding house on the corner of Richmond and Howe streets became the first school and opened  with 60 pupils. Even in the beginning, this number of children proved to be too many for the building to accommodate.  In the spring of 1902, the parish purchased the property for and work began on the colonial-type building that served as a convent and school for so many years.

In 1953 a new convent, designed by C. M. McGarvey, was built for the sisters. In 1955 Reverend James Cummings, S.M., initiated the construction of a new, larger school.  The new name, St. Francis Xavier School, replaced that of St. Joseph School as a tribute to the people of the parish who generously supported their parochial school.

Our existing red brick school located at 1121 Union Street  originally consisted of eight classrooms, a kindergarten, cafetorium and kitchen, library, book supply room, lavatories,  principal's office, health room, and teachers’ lounge. The main building surrounded a courtyard. Two new classrooms were added  in 1964. Since then further expansions included buildings for a kindergarten and preschool  and a parish hall that the parish and school share. Our dedicated faculty and staff at St. Francis Xavier School work daily to continue the mission of the Sisters of St. Joseph.

The philosophy of the center is to develop a child’s social, emotional, physical, intellectual and creative skills in a Christian, nurturing environment. To accomplish this, the CDC provides stimulating, age-appropriate learning environments, meets stringent health and safety standards and implements educationally appropriate activities and programs that fosters learning.

Serving preschool children from ages 1-year through 5-years and school-age children ages 6 through 12, Saint Philip CDC utilizes the High Reach Learning curriculum which promotes the basic learning skills of reading readiness, math concepts, health, science, music and art. As our world continues to evolve into a more technological and diverse society, Spanish lessons as well as Introduction to Computers are included in our curriculum. Other extracurricular enrichment activities offered include Dance/Ballet, Music Lab and Gymnastics.

Staff personnel attend workshops and seminars designed to keep them abreast of current strategies and concepts relative to child development and are encouraged to further their professional growth in the field.

In March of 2007, Saint Philip CDC received state accreditation and is recognized as a Center of Distinction that provides the highest quality care for children.

As an advocate of the family unit and Christian center for the care and nurturing of children, Saint Philip Child Development Center is dedicated to working together with parents to develop the whole child by teaching, with God’s guidance, the appropriate skills for children to succeed in life. That is our mission and purpose for existence.

details:
The idea for The Village was conceived in the late summer of 2013 by Blessed By Faith Online Communities, LLC. The name “The Village” is based on an African proverb, “It Takes a Village to Raise a Child”. This means not only are the parents responsible for influencing what a child becomes, but everyone else around them as well. The Village in modern terms would be a community. Although we are an online community we are dedicated to assisting in the healthy and successful upbringing of the children of the community.

The Village does not target a specific social class. It doesn’t matter if families visiting our site have a $15,000 annual income or a $250,000 income. Nor do we care if they are brown, red, white or blue. Instead, The Village celebrates the diversity of the world around us with the hope that through unity we will help and learn from each other and through our differences our community will become stronger as a whole. At The Village we believe that all children regardless of race, disability, religion, or economic background have a human right to equal opportunities that will lead them in the path of a successful future. Our main purpose is to insure that parents have knowledge of opportunities and services that will lead their children in the path to explore their dreams, talents and open the door to a future of unlimited success.

At The Village we assist parents by providing listings of businesses and organizations that specialize in services such as Child Care and Learning Centers, Special Needs Services, Private Education, Dance, Music and Arts, Sports, Clubs, Karate, Youth Organizations and Parent Training. There are a number of choices for each category listing, where there’s a match that will appeal to everyone. Blessed By Faith Online Communities, LLC pledges its dedication to our children. We do this by making an effort to aid in the future success of all the children that we serve. Because no child choses where they started from. But with the help of a strong community all children will have a choice in where or how far they go!

They benefit from being in a supportive, challenging and stimulating environment with instruction that addresses their individual uniqueness and developmental stages. Their peers without special needs are provided an opportunity to develop a realistic view of children with disabilities and an appreciation for those differences, while engaging in peer tutoring and Expedition Room Outsidestrengthening their own skills. An additional benefit of the program is the early identification or confirmation of developmental delays in children, which are often not recognized until later by the family or pediatrician; thus, delaying the intervention process. Recently, there has been a high enrollment of children diagnosed with autism spectrum disorders. Since the diagnosis of autism has no specific lab test, the Center’s competent, trained staff has played a crucial role in the early identification and intervention for these children. Our Child Development Program addresses the social, educational and developmental needs of all children so they are ready for kindergarten, with a specific emphasis on preparing the children with special needs to be mainstreamed.

details:
The Learning Tree Academy is unique in comparison to other daycare centers and childcare providers in our area, because our whole approach is to develop unique and intelligent young individuals through the strengthening of emotional, physical, and intellectual being.  We accomplish this through three basic fundamental beliefs:

They Must Know You Care Before They Care What You Know  
When it comes to teaching, our staff understand the importance of making sure each child knows he/she is special and loved.  Our staff works to create a family environment in the classroom, making sure each child that enters knows he/she has a place in our family just as they are.  The staff works to support and encourage each child as they develop and mature and do their best to help each child know they are a beautifully and wonderfully made child of God.

It Takes a Village to Raise a Child
The Learning Tree Academy was founded on the belief that it takes a village to raise a child.  While our staff do all they can to provide the best care and education possible for the development of each child, they also realize the importance of reinforcement and support from those in the home.  Through parent teacher conferences, behavior charts, assessments, and more, the staff continue to maintain a clear line of communication between school and home.  

Every Child is Unique
The staff at The Learning Tree Academy do their best to ensure each child receives the instruction and guidance that best suits his/her style of learning.  Through the incorporation of various activities which teach to different styles of learning (ex: auditory, visual, hands on) the staff work to create a learning environment that is condusive to all.

details: History is made by the people who influence it, whether positively or negatively. Now, more than ever, we are confronted with worldwide violence and dangerous political leaders, and as educators we must strive to promote awareness through positive, peaceful methods that consider all aspects of our general social systems. These systems include the administrative, safety, health, educational, family, psychological, economic, political, international and more. For me, the most important of these systems is the educational system. Therefore, my employees are trained to understand and appreciate these systems, while at the same time placing particular emphasis on the educational system. They are trained to utilize this system in an effort to break or unfreeze the boundaries of superstition, the ethnocentrism, parochialism and stereotyping. I will be helping to facilitate the implementation of this system, as well as helping the children learn professional skills. By stressing the topics of love and awareness, we believe we are putting the raw ingredients into what will become the next generation of leaders who will positively impact history. Our ultimate goal is to establish a foundation that, through education for peace, social justice, human rights and democracy, will alleviate the level of violence and coercive tactics in the world.

name: Benteen Elementary
details:
The Frederick Wilson Benteen Elementary School is located at 200 Cassanova Street, in Southeast Atlanta, Georgia. The school is part of the Atlanta Public Schools system. It belongs to the district’s East Region, and the Jackson High School Cluster. The school was opened in 1956, and deeded to the Atlanta Board of Education under the Plan of Improvement. The property where the school sits is located off of Custer Avenue, and is said to have been where the boyhood home of Mr. Benteen was located.
According to research found in Wikipedia, the school was named in memory of Mr. Frederick Wilson Benteen. Mr. Benteen was the son and only child of Major Frederick William Benteen, a military officer that served during the American Civil War under General George Custer. Young Benteen was born in Atlanta on March 27, 1867. The Major was born in Petersburg, Virginia on August 24, 1834 and died in Atlanta on June 22, 1898. Initially, Major Benteen was buried in the Westview Cemetery, a cemetery that still exists in the Southwest quadrant of Atlanta, but his body was later exhumed and reburied in Washington, D.C.

details:
The Hunter College Campus Schools are made up of Hunter College Elementary School (K-6) and Hunter College High School (7-12). We are publicly funded, selective admission schools for intellectually talented and gifted students. We aim to be a model for gifted education.

Our schools strive to reflect the city they serve by admitting and educating a population of students who are culturally, socio-economically, and ethnically diverse. We seek to serve as a model for combining excellence and equity, serving as a catalyst for change in New York City and the nation.

We serve students who demonstrate advanced cognitive ability, and we assist in the development of creative, intellectually curious, and original thinkers who are passionate about learning. We prepare our students to be life-long learners and leaders. Our schools use the principles of gifted education, including depth, complexity, challenge, enrichment, and acceleration of the curriculum, to meet the needs of intellectually advanced students. Our schools support an experienced faculty who aim to stay current in their fields and who employ developmentally appropriate pedagogy with their students.

As a community, we are committed to the social and emotional well being of all our students. We seek to develop the individual potential of each student in a collaborative atmosphere that values intellectual freedom and inspiration. We value families as partners in this work, and as partners in creating the schools’ unique environment. As a community we foster respect for and appreciation of individual and cultural differences; emphasize social responsibility and leadership, community service and good citizenship; and value civility and ethical behavior.

We believe that the greatest influence for either good or bad in the life of a child is the example that others set before him/her. We believe that the character of our staff and attitude of our Center needs to be positive, dependable, and morally excellent. Thus, at C.C.A., we expect all staff members to represent good Christian morals and maintain a positive attitude throughout the day. Our goal is that each staff member will set a good example for the children in attitude, speech, and actions.

We believe that anything worth doing is worth doing with excellence, and that there could be no more worthy cause than influencing young children to become the best that they can be. We believe that God expects us to give our very best to the next generation. Thus, at C.C.A., we strive to maintain a spirit of excellence in our facilities, curriculum, and staff. name: Petty's Preschool Daycare and Learning Center Inc
Rincon Elementary School
details:
About 1900, a “grade” school was located in Rincon, Georgia in a two-story building opposite St. John’s Lutheran Church.  Around 1905, the school was moved to the present day site of Rincon Elementary School located on Augusta Avenue (Highway 21). The new two-story school contained a steeple bell–tower. The bell was used to signal recess, lunch, and the closing of the school day. The building was known as Effingham Institute and was used for at least twenty years. During this period of time, Effingham Institute served as both a grade school and a high school. The name was changed to Rincon High School in 1920. 

In 1925, a new brick school was completed and opened in the fall of that year. The graduating class of 1925 was the last class to graduate from the old two-story wooden building. Until approximately 1928, students attended school for ten years. In 1928, the eleventh grade was added. The twelfth grade was added in 1949. Between 1956 and 1967, the old Rincon High School building was replaced by what is now the primary wing facing Fourth Street.  The Richland Avenue wing was added and opened in the fall of 1968. All of the buildings comprising Rincon Elementary School were totally renovated in 1988. A media center, music room, and two classrooms were added.  In 1999 a new wing consisting of thirteen additional classrooms, a lead teacher office, new cafeteria with a stage, and new office complex with two conference rooms, clinic, principal and assistant principal’s offices was added to meet the school’s rapidly growing population.  However, another spurt in population growth prompted an additional wing with four classrooms, a new media center, and a new gym to be added to the school, which opened in August 2003.  The old media center was converted into two new classrooms.

The population of the Rincon Elementary School continued to grow, and in 1993 the Board of Education purchased a building in the town of Rincon that had housed a sportswear factory. This building was located about a block from the Rincon Elementary School campus. The building was renovated during the summer of 1993, and in the fall of that year, the kindergarten classes were moved to this site. The state-funded pre-kindergarten was also housed in this building. The pre-kindergarten and kindergarten classes remained on this off-campus site for two years. During this time, two more elementary schools, a middle school, and a high school were built to relieve the overcrowding occurring in all Effingham schools.

In 1995, Ebenezer and Sand Hill Elementary Schools opened. Ebenezer Elementary’s district lines were drawn to reduce the student enrollment of Rincon Elementary and relieve the overcrowded conditions existing on that campus. The kindergarten and pre-kindergarten classes were moved back to the main campus.

Continued population growth in the southern end of the county soon led to an overcrowded situation at South Effingham Elementary School. Thirteen new classrooms, a new lunchroom/auditorium, new office spaces, and conference rooms were added to Rincon Elementary School in 1998. New district lines were drawn, sending students from South Effingham Elementary to Rincon Elementary.   As a result of continued growth in the Rincon, Ebenezer and South Effingham districts, a new school was built between Rincon and South Effingham Elementary School.  Blandford Elementary School opened in the fall of 2006.  Approximately half of Rincon Elementary’s students were transferred to Blandford.  Approximately two hundred students were transferred to Rincon from Ebenezer.  This change in district lines has solved our problem with overcrowding (at least temporarily).

details: The mission of Daughtry Elementary School is to build an academic and social foundation that will allow everyone here the opportunity to reach his full potential while promoting a positive self-awareness and respect for others.

name: Comer Elementary
details:
Welcome to the Comer Elementary School website.  Comer is a one great school with fantastic teachers.  Our mission is to create a caring community of learners who achieve high standards in the classroom and in life. 

We strive to offer students an exciting and rigorous learning environment that meets each student’s unique learning needs.  We value parental involvement and communication encouraging parents to be a partner in their child’s education through helping with homework, volunteering in the school, communicating with the teacher regularly, and learning about your child’s progress in the classroom.

Thanks to ESPLOST in the fall of 2012, Comer opened a new media center and classrooms.  Additionally, a new ball field and walking track is being completed in the back of the school.  Coming soon are an outdoor learning center and new playground.  We are excited about our new facilities and welcome you to stop by and visit.

We are proud of being a Title I Distinguished School and receiving the Governor’s Bronze Award for the highest percentage of students meeting and exceeding standards.  In addition to core academics we offer physical education, music, art, technology, and science enrichment for all students.  Our goal is to make school a positive place for all students to gain the skills needed to achieve in our society.

name: Jackson Elementary School
details:
Hello Jackson Elementary School Family! I would like to welcome you to the Butts County School system where we S.O.A.R here at Jackson Elementary School. For those new to the JES family, I would like to extend a very special welcome. We are all looking forward to getting to know all of our students and families throughout this school year.

The teachers and staff here at Jackson Elementary are very talented and passionate about their daily work with our students.  Everyone's primary goal here at JES is to provide the most effective instructional programs and a successful learning community for all of our students.  At JES our teachers continue their professional learning throughout each school year in many ways to fine-tune and learn more about the best teaching strategies for your children. Each year the teachers examine and analyze test data and various other forms of data to determine the most effective instructional strategies for the students in their classrooms. This process continues throughout the school year, and as a result, the teachers collaboratively plan and develop instructional lessons which address the multiple learning styles and learning needs for all of our students.

We have many exciting activities and changes planned for this school year. We solicit your input and support throughout the year. At Open House, as well as the first few weeks of school, you will be given an opportunity to join the wonderful JES PTO. I would like to encourage you to do so. It is essential that we, as a family, work together to collectively reach our goals for our students and our school.

name: Saddle Ridge Elementary
details: Walker County Schools in LaFayette, Georgia. "Ensuring all Students Graduate; Ready for College, Ready for Work, Ready for Life". We are convinced that graduation is the key to future success and the success of our community, state and nation.

details:
Mission:  Working together to teach students in a safe, orderly, and challenging environment, inspiring them to learn and excel.
